DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The territorial rights literature asks what justifies a state's (or other political entity's) jurisdiction over a particular geographical territory. Recent scholarship has moved beyond state-level analysis to examine sub-state territorial claims, including neighborhood-level occupancy rights in gentrification contexts. Major theoretical traditions include: (1) nationalist theories grounding rights in cultural nations' relationships with homelands (Miller, Meisels); (2) self-determination theories connecting territorial rights to peoples' capacity for self-governance and occupancy (Moore, Stilz); (3) place-based or "river model" theories emphasizing ecological features and dense social relationships (Nine, Ochoa Espejo); and (4) associative ownership theories based on contributions to political institutions (Pevnick). A parallel literature on the philosophy of place (Malpas, Casey) provides phenomenological foundations for understanding the normative significance of place attachment, arguing that human being is inextricably bound to place and that this attachment grounds moral claims.

The mobility-stability tension emerges in debates about migration rights versus rights to remain in place. Cosmopolitan theorists (Benhabib) emphasize universal hospitality and porous borders, while communitarians stress the moral significance of rootedness and local attachments. Recent work has applied territorial rights frameworks to urban gentrification, arguing that residents have occupancy rights against displacement (Huber & Wolkenstein 2018, Krishnamurthy & Moore 2024). Climate displacement raises urgent questions about whether territorial rights include rights to remain when environmental change threatens habitability (Stilz 2024).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is directly relevant to housing justice and temporal claims research because it addresses whether long-term residence generates moral claims to remain in a place. If occupancy theory is correct that people develop place-based life projects deserving protection, then temporal duration of residence becomes morally significant for housing policy. The literature provides sophisticated frameworks for thinking about neighborhood-level territorial claims, not just state-level borders. The tension between mobility (freedom to move) and stability (freedom to stay put) maps onto housing displacement debates where some emphasize economic mobility while others stress community rootedness and the right to stay put.

RECENT_DEVELOPMENTS:
The last decade has seen an "urban turn" in territorial rights theory, with philosophers applying occupancy rights frameworks to gentrification and neighborhood change (Huber & Wolkenstein 2018, Krishnamurthy & Moore 2024, Draper 2024). Climate displacement has prompted new work on territorial justice when places become uninhabitable (Stilz 2024). A 2025 special issue in Critical Review of International Social and Political Philosophy advances "second wave" territorial rights theory engaging gentrification, Indigenous land rights, and foundational territories for resource management (Nine 2025). There is growing interest in place-based rights as distinct from property rights, with emphasis on how displacement harms autonomy by disrupting place-dependent life plans.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Most territorial rights theory focuses on state-level or Indigenous peoples' claims, with limited work on intermediate scales like cities and neighborhoods. Few theorists have operationalized "occupancy" or "attachment" in ways that guide policy. The relationship between temporal duration and strength of territorial claim remains under-theorized. Little work bridges phenomenological accounts of place (Malpas, Casey) with normative political theory, despite potential synergies. The tension between cosmopolitan mobility rights and localist stability rights needs more systematic treatment, especially regarding housing.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Focus on Stilz's occupancy theory (2009, 2019, 2024) as the core philosophical framework, particularly her account of how place-based life projects ground territorial claims. Contrast self-determination theories (Moore, Stilz) with place-based "river model" approaches (Nine, Ochoa Espejo). The recent gentrification literature (Huber & Wolkenstein 2018, Krishnamurthy & Moore 2024) shows how territorial rights theory applies to housing, making it essential for the state-of-the-art review. Phenomenological work (Malpas, Casey) provides deeper grounding for why place matters morally but needs integration with normative theory. The mobility-stability tension (Kotef 2015, Benhabib 2006) frames a core dilemma for housing justice.

KEY_POSITIONS:
